<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Characteristic Species</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Lepidospartum</i> <i>squamatum</i> is dominant, co-dominant,
or conspicuous in the shrub canopy with <i>Ambrosia</i> <i>salsola</i>, <i>Artemisia</i> <i>californica</i>, <i>Baccharis</i> <i>salicifolia</i>, <i>Cleome</i> <i>isomeris</i>, <i>Cylindropuntia</i> <i>californica</i>, <i>Encelia</i> <i>farinosa</i>, <i>Eriodictyon</i> <i>crassifolium</i>, <i>Eriodictyon</i> <i>trichocalyx</i>, <i>Eriogonum</i> <i>fasciculatum</i>, <i>Hesperoyucca</i> <i>whipplei</i>, <i>Lotus</i> <i>scoparius</i>, <i>Malosma</i> <i>laurina</i>, <i>Opuntia</i> <i>littoralis</i>, <i>Rhus</i> <i>integrifolia</i>, <i>Rhus</i> <i>ovata</i>, <i>Rhus</i> <i>trilobata</i> and <i>Toxicodendron</i> <i>diversilobum</i>. Emergent trees or tall shrubs may be present at low cover, including <i>Cercocarpus</i> <i>montanus</i>, <i>Juglans</i> <i>californica</i>, <i>Juniperus</i> <i>californica</i>, <i>Platanus</i> <i>racemosa</i>, <i>Populus</i> <i>fremontii</i> or <i>Sambucus</i> <i>nigra</i>. </div>
</div>

        
	
<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Vegetation Layers</h4>
	<div class="text">  Shrubs < 2 m; canopy is open to continuous, and two tiered. Herbaceous layer is variable and may be grassy. </div>
</div>

        
<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Membership Rules</h4>
	<ul class="text">
		
		<li><i>Lepidospartum squamatum</i> > 1% cover in alluvial environments (Barbour and Wirka 1997, AECOM 2019).</li>
		
	</ul>
</div>

        
	
<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Habitats</h4>
	<div class="text"> Intermittently or rarely flooded, low-gradient alluvial deposits along streams, washes, and fans. The USFWS Wetland Inventory (1996 national list) recognizes <i>Lepidospartum squamatum</i> as a NI plant. </div>
</div>

        
