    <div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
        <h4 class="header">Regional Status</h4>
        

        <ul class="text">
        
            <li><b>Central California Coast Ranges</b> (M262Ad, Ag-j). Stands in western Fresno and eastern San Benito Cos. contain coastal scrub and disturbance-related species, and they are more likely to occur along intermittent creeks as far north as eastern Alameda Co. Stands were surveyed in the Pleasant Valley Ecological Reserve (Buck-Diaz et al 2012).</li>
        
            <li><b>Great Valley</b> (262Ag, Aq, Aw, Ay-z). Stands were mapped and surveyed in drainages rimming the southern San Joaquin Valley on the east, west and south, including around the Kern River, Poso Creek, and Cantua Creek (GIC 2013 and VegCAMP 2015).</li>
        
            <li><b>Mojave Desert</b> (322Af-h, An). Stands of <i>Lepidospartum squamatum</i>/ephemeral annuals association occur near the eastern boundaries of the southern Sierra Nevada and northern boundaries of the Transverse Ranges (Barbour and Wirka 1997). Some of the best stands occur at Red Rock Canyon State Recreation Area in Big Rock Wash. The alliance occurs in wide, active washes in Fremont and Indian Wells Valleys, lower El Paso Mountains and the north side of the Lava Mountains (Menke et al. 2013).</li>
        
            <li><b>Sierra Nevada</b> (M261Er-s). Stands exist along Cottonwood Creek in Kern Co., and were mapped along drainages surrounding in the Tehachapi and Piute Mountains (VegCAMP 2015a).</li>
        
            <li><b>Sierra Nevada Foothills</b> (M261Fd-e). Stands occur near Lake Isabella in Kern Co.</li>
        
            <li><b>Southern California Coast</b> (261Bb, Bd-g, Bi-j). Stands once occurred along intermittent streams and gently sloping fans in Los Angeles and Orange Cos., but few remain. The alliance occurs sparingly in the Santa Monica Mountains (Keeler-Wolf and Evens 2006). Stands were surveyed in Camp Pendleton (AECOM 2019).</li>
        
            <li><b>Southern California Mountains and Valleys</b> (M262Ba-d, Bf-l, Bp). Stands exist along the few remaining alluvial fans in interior subsections in association with <i>Eriogonum fasciculatum, Eriodictyon trichocalyx,</i> and <i>Hesperoyucca whipplei.</i> The CNPS 1B plants <i>Eriastrum densifolium</i> ssp. <i>sanctorum</i> and <i>Dodecahema leptoceras</i> occur in some stands. Stands occur in the Gavilan Hills (Boyd 1983), in Cucamonga and San Gabriel Canyons and along the San Jacinto River (Hanes et al. 1989), along the San Gabriel River floodplain (Smith 1980), San Gabriel and San Bernardino Mountain fans and floodplains (Rundel 2007), in western Riverside Co. (Klein and Evens 2005), and generally for the section (Barbour and Wirka 1997).  <i>Baccharis sarothroides</i> alliance replaces <i>Lepidospartum squamatum </i>in similar conditions in San Diego County (Smith 1996).</li>
        
        </ul>
    </div>


    
	
<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Management Considerations</h4>
	<div class="text"> Interruption of natural fluvial processes in this alliance occurs extensively in southern California from construction of houses and golf courses, agriculture, dams, gravel mining, and stream channelization. Interruption of natural processes is less frequent in the desert areas. Some building departments require pre-construction surveys and eradication of <i>Lepidospartum squamatum </i>due to its strong sprouting ability, perhaps even through pavement. 

The destruction of many older stands are a cause for much concern. While recent conservation acquisitions have preserved some stands, upstream dams and flood control modifications do not bode well for stand persistence. </div>
</div>

    

    

